n from the Maghrib to the Mashriq -- tAndalusi Romance Terms in Kitāb al-Simāt fī asmāʾ al-nabāt, by al-Suwaydī of Damascus (d. 690 H/1291 CE) -- tThe Influence of Andalusi Ṣūfism on the Central Islamicate World: Ibn Sabʿīn's son and his Kitāb al-Sulūk fī ṭarīq al-qawm -- tIsnād of Ibn Khaldūn: Maghribi Tradition of Knowledge in Mamlūk Cairo -- tMālikī Jurists from the Maghrib and al- Andalus in Post-Fāṭimid Egypt -- tTraces of the Medieval Islamic West in Modern East Africa: Andalusi and Maghribi Works in the Horn of Africa -- tPart V: Remaining Maghribi while in the Mashriq -- tVehicles of Cultural Identity: Some Thoughts on Maghribi Scripts and Manuscripts in the Mashriq -- tA Mamlūk-Andalusi Holograph Manuscript of the Former Marīnid Chancellor Muḥammad Ibn Ḥizb Allāh al-Wādī Āshī (d. 788 H/1386 CE) -- tWriting the Biography of Ibn Khaldūn -- tIndex of Names and Places0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis is a pioneering book about the impact that knowledge produced in the Maghrib (Islamic North Africa and al-Andalus = Muslim Iberia) had on the rest of the Islamic world. It presents results achieved in the Research Project "Local contexts and global dynamics: al-Andalus and the Maghrib in the Islamic East (AMOI)", funded by the Spanish Ministry of Science, Innovation and Universities (FFI2016-78878-R AEI/FEDER, UE) and directed by Maribel Fierro and Mayte Penelas. The book contains 18 contributions written by senior and junior scholars from different institutions all over the world. It is divided into five sections dealing with how knowledge produced in the Maghrib was integrated in the Mashriq starting with the emergence and construction of the concept 'Maghrib' (sections 1 and 2); how travel allowed the reception in the Maghrib of knowledge produced in the Mashriq but also the transmission of locally produced knowledge outside the Maghrib, and the different ways in which such transmission took place (sections 3 and 4), and how the Maghribis who stayed or settled in the Mashriq manifested their identity (section 5). The book will be of interest not only for those whose research concentrates on the Maghrib but more generally for those who want to understand the complex and shifting dynamics between 'centres' and 'peripheries' as regards intellectual production and circulation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 7aRELIGION / Islam / History.2bisacsh1 aAdang, Camilla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAzgal, Zohra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBellver, José, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBockholt, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBongianino, Umberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalasso, Giovanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastro León, Víctor de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFierro, Maribel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFierro, Maribel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGarulo, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHernández López, Adday, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIto, Takao, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoguchi, Maiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPadillo-Saoud, Abdenour, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb